This paper involves the application of non-orthogonal multiple access (NOMA) to ALOHA, which is a random access scheme commonly used in the Internet of Things (IoT). Therefore, the most likely category is cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). The paper also involves the use of game theory to formulate a strategy for transmission probability, which falls under the category of cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). The paper also involves the use of energy-efficiency metrics, which falls under the category of cs.SY (Systems and Control). Additionally, the paper involves the use of successive interference cancellation (SIC), which falls under the category of cs.IT (Information Theory). Finally, the paper involves the application of NOMA to improve spectral efficiency, which falls under the category of cs.MM (Multimedia).
